04813nam a22006255i 9780226422817DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264228177 a10.7208/97802264228172doi  a(DE-B1597)523247  a(OCoLC)988326331  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGA108.7b.D44 2018 7aTEC0000002bisacsh04a52622300aDecolonizing the Map :bCartography from Colony to Nation /cJames R. Akerman. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b121 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Kenneth Nebenzahl Jr. Lectures in the History of Cartography00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tINTRODUCTION -- tCHAPTER ONE. Cartography and Decolonization / rCraib, Raymond B. -- tCHAPTER TWO. Entangled Spaces: Mapping Multiple Identities in Eighteenth- Century New Spain / rCarrera, Magali -- tCHAPTER THREE. Cartography in the Production (and Silencing) of Colombian Independence History, 1807- 1827 / rCastillo, Lina del -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Democratizing the Map: The Geo- body and National Cartography in Guatemala, 1821- 2010 / rDym, Jordana -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Uncovering the Roles of African Surveyors and Draftsmen in Mapping the Gold Coast, 1874-1957 / rMcGowan, Jamie -- tCHAPTER SIX. Multiscalar Nations: Cartography and Countercartography of the Egyptian Nation- State / rCulcasi, Karen -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Art on the Line: Cartography and Creativity in a Divided World / rRamaswamy, Sumathi -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Signs of the Times: Commercial Road Mapping and National Identity in South Africa / rBassett, Thomas J. -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlmost universally, newly independent states seek to affirm their independence and identity by making the production of new maps and atlases a top priority. For formerly colonized peoples, however, this process neither begins nor ends with independence, and it is rarely straightforward. Mapping their own land is fraught with a fresh set of issues: how to define and administer their territories, develop their national identity, establish their role in the community of nations, and more. The contributors to Decolonizing the Map explore this complicated relationship between mapping and decolonization while engaging with recent theoretical debates about the nature of decolonization itself.   These essays, originally delivered as the 2010 Kenneth Nebenzahl, Jr., Lectures in the History of Cartography at the Newberry Library, encompass more than two centuries and three continents-Latin America, Africa, and Asia. Ranging from the late eighteenth century through the mid-twentieth, contributors study topics from mapping and national identity in late colonial Mexico to the enduring complications created by the partition of British India and the racialized organization of space in apartheid and post-apartheid South Africa. A vital contribution to studies of both colonization and cartography, Decolonizing the Map is the first book to systematically and comprehensively examine the engagement of mapping in the long-and clearly unfinished-parallel processes of decolonization and nation building in the modern world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCartographyxPolitical aspects. 0aDecolonization. 4aAfrica. 4aAsia. 4aLatin America. 4acartography. 4acolonies. 4acountermapping. 4acreoles. 4adecolonization. 4anation-state. 4aterritory. 7aTechnology & Engineering / General.2bisacsh1 aAkerman, James R., eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruy